00:01:10.180 --> 00:01:32.092 align:middle line:90%


00:01:32.092 --> 00:01:34.084 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:34.084 --> 00:01:38.760 align:middle line:90%


00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:39.460 align:middle line:90%
Hey there.

00:01:39.460 --> 00:01:41.170 align:middle line:84%
Welcome to this episode
of "Mind Shift."

00:01:41.170 --> 00:01:42.620 align:middle line:10%
I'm Daniel Pinchbeck,
and today we'll

00:01:42.620 --> 00:01:46.240 align:middle line:10%
be interviewing, discussing
with Howard Bloom, author

00:01:46.240 --> 00:01:48.590 align:middle line:10%
of "The Lucifer Principle,"
"The God Problem,"

00:01:48.590 --> 00:01:50.220 align:middle line:10%
and a number of other books.

00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:54.460 align:middle line:84%
We'll then be introducing Howard
to two young entrepreneurs,

00:01:54.460 --> 00:01:56.900 align:middle line:90%
Amber Lasciak and Miki Agrawal.

00:01:56.900 --> 00:01:58.690 align:middle line:84%
NARRATOR: Bloom's
fascination with science

00:01:58.690 --> 00:01:59.870 align:middle line:90%
started at a young age.

00:01:59.870 --> 00:02:01.950 align:middle line:84%
And he dove into the
study of microbiology,

00:02:01.950 --> 00:02:04.910 align:middle line:84%
theoretical physics, and
cosmology at the age of 10.

00:02:04.910 --> 00:02:06.810 align:middle line:84%
At 16 he worked
as a lab assistant

00:02:06.810 --> 00:02:09.139 align:middle line:84%
in the world's largest
cancer research facility

00:02:09.139 --> 00:02:11.170 align:middle line:84%
and went on to graduate
Magna Cum Laude

00:02:11.170 --> 00:02:13.530 align:middle line:90%
and Phi Beta Kappa from NYU.

00:02:13.530 --> 00:02:15.410 align:middle line:84%
He then did the
unthinkable and turned down

00:02:15.410 --> 00:02:17.980 align:middle line:84%
four graduate school fellowships
to form his own music

00:02:17.980 --> 00:02:19.840 align:middle line:90%
publicity company.

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:21.330 align:middle line:84%
The Howard Bloom
Organization became

00:02:21.330 --> 00:02:22.820 align:middle line:84%
one of the top
publicity companies

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:24.130 align:middle line:90%
in the music industry.

00:02:24.130 --> 00:02:26.260 align:middle line:84%
And Howard was instrumental
in building or sustaining

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:28.480 align:middle line:84%
the careers of Prince,
Michael Jackson,

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:34.600 align:middle line:84%
Bob Marley, Paul Simon, Queen,
KISS, AC/DC, among many others.

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:36.960 align:middle line:10%
He also has written several
well-respected and widely

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:40.240 align:middle line:10%
successful books-- "The Lucifer
Principle," "A Scientific

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:42.540 align:middle line:10%
Exploration in the
Forces of History,"

00:02:42.540 --> 00:02:44.880 align:middle line:10%
"The Genius of the
Beast-- A Radical Revision

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.610 align:middle line:10%
of Capitalism," "Global Brain--
The Evolution of the Mass

00:02:48.610 --> 00:02:51.270 align:middle line:10%
Mind From the Big Bang
to the 21st Century,"

00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:54.960 align:middle line:10%
and "The God Problem-- How
a Godless Cosmos Creates."

00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:57.730 align:middle line:10%
Howard Bloom is considered by
many to be one of the greatest

00:02:57.730 --> 00:02:58.780 align:middle line:10%
living thinkers.

00:02:58.780 --> 00:03:01.540 align:middle line:10%
And according to Britain's
Channel 4, next in a lineage

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:03.810 align:middle line:10%
of seminal thinkers
that includes Newton,

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:05.660 align:middle line:10%
Darwin, Einstein, and Freud.

00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:09.034 align:middle line:90%


00:03:09.034 --> 00:03:10.962 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:10.962 --> 00:03:13.870 align:middle line:90%


00:03:13.870 --> 00:03:15.370 align:middle line:84%
Howard, thank you so
much for joining us.

00:03:15.370 --> 00:03:16.730 align:middle line:84%
-It's great to see you.
-It's great to see you.

00:03:16.730 --> 00:03:18.250 align:middle line:84%
When we originally met
a number of years ago,

00:03:18.250 --> 00:03:19.180 align:middle line:90%
I think I visited you.

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:20.590 align:middle line:84%
And you were bedridden
at that point.

00:03:20.590 --> 00:03:22.560 align:middle line:84%
Absolutely stuck
in bed for 15 years.

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:24.690 align:middle line:10%
And for five years,
too weak to speak,

00:03:24.690 --> 00:03:26.330 align:middle line:10%
too weak to have another
person in the room.

00:03:26.330 --> 00:03:28.510 align:middle line:84%
You came in when I was
able to talk again.

00:03:28.510 --> 00:03:30.190 align:middle line:90%
It was-- what was the syndrome?

00:03:30.190 --> 00:03:31.405 align:middle line:90%
It's chronic fatigue syndrome.

00:03:31.405 --> 00:03:32.105 align:middle line:90%
It's vicious.

00:03:32.105 --> 00:03:32.865 align:middle line:90%
It's nasty.

00:03:32.865 --> 00:03:33.660 align:middle line:90%
It's brutal.

00:03:33.660 --> 00:03:37.060 align:middle line:84%
And it teaches you all kinds
of amazing lessons about life.

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:38.960 align:middle line:84%
And how did you finally shake
it, just out of curiosity?

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:39.720 align:middle line:90%
A good question.

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:43.050 align:middle line:84%
A combination of
drugs, pharmaceuticals

00:03:43.050 --> 00:03:46.910 align:middle line:84%
from big pharma, specifically
one called Gabapentin.

00:03:46.910 --> 00:03:49.670 align:middle line:84%
Another drug that I have to
give myself a shot of every day.

00:03:49.670 --> 00:03:51.130 align:middle line:90%
It's oxytocin.

00:03:51.130 --> 00:03:52.250 align:middle line:90%
It's the social hormone.

00:03:52.250 --> 00:03:53.770 align:middle line:90%
It's the bonding hormone.

00:03:53.770 --> 00:03:55.200 align:middle line:90%
Makes a huge difference.

00:03:55.200 --> 00:03:57.720 align:middle line:90%
And God knows what else, Daniel.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:03:58.770 align:middle line:90%
Oh.

00:03:58.770 --> 00:04:02.326 align:middle line:84%
So tell us a little
bit about Howard Bloom.

00:04:02.326 --> 00:04:03.025 align:middle line:90%
Who is he?

00:04:03.025 --> 00:04:05.030 align:middle line:84%
What are all-- what are all
these-- these massive tomes?

00:04:05.030 --> 00:04:08.990 align:middle line:84%
Well, I was a kid who nobody
wanted in Buffalo, New York,

00:04:08.990 --> 00:04:12.330 align:middle line:84%
when I was a little kid,
this grim industrial town.

00:04:12.330 --> 00:04:16.529 align:middle line:84%
And at the age of 10, when
I was very, very alone

00:04:16.529 --> 00:04:18.470 align:middle line:84%
and very, very
depressed, two guys

00:04:18.470 --> 00:04:21.120 align:middle line:90%
reached out to save my life.

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:23.510 align:middle line:84%
One was they reached
out through books.

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:25.360 align:middle line:90%
One was Galileo.

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:28.330 align:middle line:84%
And the other one was
Antonie van Leeuwenhoek.

00:04:28.330 --> 00:04:30.710 align:middle line:84%
And a book that
appeared on my lap

00:04:30.710 --> 00:04:33.950 align:middle line:84%
one day, in my great
big living room

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:36.780 align:middle line:84%
said, the first two principles
of science, the first two rules

00:04:36.780 --> 00:04:39.620 align:middle line:84%
of science are these--
the truth at any price,

00:04:39.620 --> 00:04:41.380 align:middle line:84%
including the
price of your life.

00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:43.000 align:middle line:90%
And that resonated with me.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:44.580 align:middle line:90%
It was a law of courage.

00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:46.710 align:middle line:84%
And the second
law of science was

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:48.100 align:middle line:84%
look at things right
under your nose

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:49.960 align:middle line:84%
as if you've never
seen them before.

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:51.900 align:middle line:84%
Look at things that you
and everybody around you

00:04:51.900 --> 00:04:54.740 align:middle line:84%
take for granted as if you
have never seen them before.

00:04:54.740 --> 00:04:56.350 align:middle line:90%
And then proceed from there.

00:04:56.350 --> 00:04:57.570 align:middle line:90%
And that was it.

00:04:57.570 --> 00:05:01.950 align:middle line:84%
I had a religion, those
two laws, science.

00:05:01.950 --> 00:05:03.840 align:middle line:84%
And my life was
saved by two guys

00:05:03.840 --> 00:05:07.120 align:middle line:84%
who had reached out over 350
years to grab me before I fell.

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:08.180 align:middle line:90%
Nice.

00:05:08.180 --> 00:05:11.420 align:middle line:84%
If there was-- if you were
to sum up all the books that

00:05:11.420 --> 00:05:14.200 align:middle line:84%
you've-- that you've written
and the thoughts that

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:16.890 align:middle line:84%
you've assimilated in,
like, a concise paragraph,

00:05:16.890 --> 00:05:20.680 align:middle line:84%
what would you say kind of,
like, your project is in a way?

00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:24.190 align:middle line:84%
My project is to take
every single science

00:05:24.190 --> 00:05:26.320 align:middle line:84%
that a limited
brain can possibly

00:05:26.320 --> 00:05:29.760 align:middle line:84%
grasp, to put them together
with all the history

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:31.430 align:middle line:90%
that you can possibly assemble.

00:05:31.430 --> 00:05:34.020 align:middle line:84%
I've been assembling
it for 60 years now.

00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:35.760 align:middle line:90%
I'm 70 years old.

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:39.330 align:middle line:84%
And with all of the arts, all
of the insights from the arts,

00:05:39.330 --> 00:05:42.700 align:middle line:84%
all of the insights from your
territories, from mysticism,

00:05:42.700 --> 00:05:45.790 align:middle line:84%
put them together
into a big picture

00:05:45.790 --> 00:05:48.980 align:middle line:84%
to fashion new lenses with which
people could see everything

00:05:48.980 --> 00:05:51.020 align:middle line:84%
inside of them and
everything around them

00:05:51.020 --> 00:05:53.200 align:middle line:84%
in ways they've never
imagined before.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:55.150 align:middle line:84%
And what's the
ultimate advantage

00:05:55.150 --> 00:05:57.640 align:middle line:84%
of having that new lens
or that new perspective?

00:05:57.640 --> 00:05:59.560 align:middle line:84%
The ultimate advantage
to the individual

00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:01.890 align:middle line:84%
is that one of the greatest
things in the world, one

00:06:01.890 --> 00:06:04.375 align:middle line:84%
of the most exhilarating
things you can possibly possess

00:06:04.375 --> 00:06:06.101 align:middle line:90%
is insight.

00:06:06.101 --> 00:06:09.170 align:middle line:84%
Insight every day, being able
to look at the pen in your hand

00:06:09.170 --> 00:06:11.970 align:middle line:84%
and suddenly see it as if you've
never seen-- seen it before,

00:06:11.970 --> 00:06:14.230 align:middle line:90%
as if it's a freaking miracle.

00:06:14.230 --> 00:06:19.490 align:middle line:84%
And in addition, to be able
to get an intellectual sense.

00:06:19.490 --> 00:06:21.070 align:middle line:90%
Not just a sense of wonder.

00:06:21.070 --> 00:06:24.070 align:middle line:84%
Not just a sense of awe,
but a sense of where it fits

00:06:24.070 --> 00:06:25.960 align:middle line:90%
in the world, in a new way.

00:06:25.960 --> 00:06:28.920 align:middle line:84%
That's one of the greatest
highs you can possibly imagine.

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:30.950 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's go through
a few of the books just

00:06:30.950 --> 00:06:33.280 align:middle line:90%
step-- one by one here.

00:06:33.280 --> 00:06:37.770 align:middle line:84%
"The Lucifer Principle,"
what was basically your sort

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:39.070 align:middle line:90%
of thrust with that book?

00:06:39.070 --> 00:06:41.835 align:middle line:84%
Well, Dorion Sagan
and Lynn Marguilis.

00:06:41.835 --> 00:06:43.805 align:middle line:84%
Dorion Sagan is Carl
Sagan's oldest son.

00:06:43.805 --> 00:06:46.310 align:middle line:84%
Lynn Margulis was
Dorion Sagan's mother

00:06:46.310 --> 00:06:47.900 align:middle line:90%
and Carl Sagan's first wife.

00:06:47.900 --> 00:06:52.350 align:middle line:84%
And she's a National Medal
of Science winning biologist.

00:06:52.350 --> 00:06:55.360 align:middle line:84%
The two of them had written an
article in which they exalted

00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:56.920 align:middle line:84%
over a mass die
off that happened

00:06:56.920 --> 00:06:58.870 align:middle line:90%
roughly two billion years ago.

00:06:58.870 --> 00:07:01.890 align:middle line:84%
And it exalted over it
because it's the mass

00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:03.280 align:middle line:84%
die off that made
the kinds of cells

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:05.020 align:middle line:90%
that make you and me up today.

00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:06.750 align:middle line:90%
This is when the [INAUDIBLE]--

00:07:06.750 --> 00:07:08.035 align:middle line:84%
This is The Great
Oxygen Catastrophe.

00:07:08.035 --> 00:07:09.110 align:middle line:84%
-Right, right, right.
-Yeah.

00:07:09.110 --> 00:07:10.620 align:middle line:84%
It's when--
-Can you explain what happened?

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:13.700 align:middle line:84%
It's when-- cyanobacteria,
for about 2 billion years,

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:16.170 align:middle line:84%
have been pulling off
a goddamned miracle.

00:07:16.170 --> 00:07:20.360 align:middle line:84%
They have been snatching photons
which could destroy things.

00:07:20.360 --> 00:07:23.190 align:middle line:84%
They've been snatching
radiation from the air

00:07:23.190 --> 00:07:25.680 align:middle line:84%
and knitting it together with
elements of the air and water

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:29.460 align:middle line:84%
and creating bio stuff, creating
cell stuff, creating life.

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:32.110 align:middle line:84%
And the problem was there
was stuff they could process.

00:07:32.110 --> 00:07:34.050 align:middle line:84%
There was stuff they
couldn't process.

00:07:34.050 --> 00:07:35.905 align:middle line:84%
So they took the stuff
they could process.

00:07:35.905 --> 00:07:39.280 align:middle line:84%
And they turned out life and
more life and even more life.

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:40.095 align:middle line:90%
And it was an amazement.

00:07:40.095 --> 00:07:42.150 align:middle line:90%
It was a wonder.

00:07:42.150 --> 00:07:43.680 align:middle line:84%
But they had to
fart out the stuff

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:46.290 align:middle line:90%
that they could not process.

00:07:46.290 --> 00:07:47.640 align:middle line:90%
It was a toxic waste.

00:07:47.640 --> 00:07:50.760 align:middle line:84%
Now, look, a colony--
bacteria-living colonies,

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:51.750 align:middle line:90%
they're not individuals.

00:07:51.750 --> 00:07:52.730 align:middle line:90%
They live in big groups.

00:07:52.730 --> 00:07:54.750 align:middle line:84%
And they're groups of
seven trillion, roughly.

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:57.200 align:middle line:84%
More-- more-- more
bacteria in one

00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:00.110 align:middle line:84%
group than all the humans who've
ever lived on planet Earth.

00:08:00.110 --> 00:08:02.580 align:middle line:84%
And one of those colonies could
fit on the palm of your hand.

00:08:02.580 --> 00:08:05.670 align:middle line:84%
And it can be so thin
that you cannot see.

00:08:05.670 --> 00:08:06.820 align:middle line:90%
It's invisible.

00:08:06.820 --> 00:08:09.390 align:middle line:84%
So the farts of a
bunch of bacteria

00:08:09.390 --> 00:08:12.530 align:middle line:84%
whose entire colonies are so
thin you can't even see them?

00:08:12.530 --> 00:08:14.140 align:middle line:84%
What's that going to
amount to on a planet

00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:16.060 align:middle line:84%
with a huge atmosphere?
Nothing.

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:17.780 align:middle line:84%
Well, eventually, over
two billion years,

00:08:17.780 --> 00:08:19.400 align:middle line:90%
the farts built up.

00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:20.675 align:middle line:84%
And they built up
to the point where

00:08:20.675 --> 00:08:23.290 align:middle line:84%
we had a toxically-polluted
atmosphere.

00:08:23.290 --> 00:08:25.505 align:middle line:84%
And the atmosphere was
killing off the bacteria.

00:08:25.505 --> 00:08:29.060 align:middle line:84%
It was killing off the first
life forms on this planet.

00:08:29.060 --> 00:08:31.360 align:middle line:84%
And that was called--
well, we won't go into what

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:32.789 align:middle line:90%
it was called for a second.

00:08:32.789 --> 00:08:36.940 align:middle line:84%
Some bacteria worked
out a very clever deal.

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:38.179 align:middle line:84%
There were
teenie-weenie bacteria

00:08:38.179 --> 00:08:39.880 align:middle line:84%
that knew how to take
this toxic pollutant

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:42.890 align:middle line:84%
and actually turn it into
stuff that could make energy.

00:08:42.890 --> 00:08:45.510 align:middle line:84%
So the big bacteria made a
deal with the little bacteria.

00:08:45.510 --> 00:08:46.480 align:middle line:90%
You live inside of us.

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:48.030 align:middle line:84%
We'll find you the
greatest places

00:08:48.030 --> 00:08:49.380 align:middle line:90%
you ever imagined to live.

00:08:49.380 --> 00:08:52.320 align:middle line:84%
We'll get you every resource
you ever imagined in life.

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:54.950 align:middle line:84%
We'll keep you feasting
and happy like crazy.

00:08:54.950 --> 00:08:58.010 align:middle line:84%
You just feed us
what you shit out.

00:08:58.010 --> 00:08:59.260 align:middle line:84%
Because what they
shat out-- what

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:00.790 align:middle line:84%
these little tiny
things that feasted

00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:02.440 align:middle line:84%
on the toxic
pollutants shat out--

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:05.800 align:middle line:84%
were ambrosia to
the big bacteria.

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:09.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, that toxic pollutant--
the big, first, really big

00:09:09.890 --> 00:09:13.110 align:middle line:84%
toxic pollutant catastrophe
in the history of the planet--

00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:16.570 align:middle line:84%
that toxic pollutant was
called oxygen. And there's

00:09:16.570 --> 00:09:19.890 align:middle line:84%
a lesson in that, which
is every toxic pollutant

00:09:19.890 --> 00:09:21.890 align:middle line:90%
is a fuel waiting to be found.

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:23.000 align:middle line:90%
It's a resource.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.620 align:middle line:84%
It is-- it's a feast
waiting to be discovered.

00:09:26.620 --> 00:09:28.820 align:middle line:84%
I mean, one idea you discussed
in "The Lucifer Principle"

00:09:28.820 --> 00:09:32.070 align:middle line:84%
is kind of conceiving
of evil differently.

00:09:32.070 --> 00:09:35.770 align:middle line:84%
When they wrote
exultantly about this mass

00:09:35.770 --> 00:09:37.970 align:middle line:84%
die off that killed off
almost everything on Earth,

00:09:37.970 --> 00:09:40.633 align:middle line:84%
I thought what did we
learn from World War II?

00:09:40.633 --> 00:09:44.650 align:middle line:84%
You don't stand by and exalt
over a mass murder of any kind.

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:47.580 align:middle line:84%
You rebel against it with
all your heart and soul.

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:52.090 align:middle line:84%
So I wrote a book specifically
about mass murder,

00:09:52.090 --> 00:09:55.520 align:middle line:84%
about hatred, about
violence, about war,

00:09:55.520 --> 00:10:00.910 align:middle line:84%
about it's evolutionary origins,
about how essential evil is

00:10:00.910 --> 00:10:04.070 align:middle line:84%
to nature, and how essential
it is that we oppose

00:10:04.070 --> 00:10:07.010 align:middle line:90%
nature to make nature just.

00:10:07.010 --> 00:10:09.330 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about
that opposing of nature.

00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:10.690 align:middle line:90%
What does that mean exactly?

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:13.790 align:middle line:84%
Well, it meant, in the case
of the bacteria that managed

00:10:13.790 --> 00:10:16.170 align:middle line:84%
to escape the Great
Oxygen Catastrophe,

00:10:16.170 --> 00:10:18.950 align:middle line:84%
taking something that
seemed brutally unnatural,

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:22.530 align:middle line:84%
this poisonous gas, oxygen,
and turning it into the source

00:10:22.530 --> 00:10:23.230 align:middle line:90%
of the next paradise.

00:10:23.230 --> 00:10:24.910 align:middle line:84%
What does it mean
for human beings?

00:10:24.910 --> 00:10:28.470 align:middle line:84%
What it means for human beings
is re-conceiving everything

00:10:28.470 --> 00:10:29.880 align:middle line:84%
around us that we
were regard as dark

00:10:29.880 --> 00:10:33.690 align:middle line:84%
and ominous as a
potential resource.

00:10:33.690 --> 00:10:35.740 align:middle line:84%
Including, for
example, right now

00:10:35.740 --> 00:10:38.760 align:middle line:84%
our major concern is the carbon
dioxide in the atmosphere.

00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:40.960 align:middle line:84%
Another major concern
is global warming.

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:43.240 align:middle line:84%
Look, nature's taken
advantage of global warming

00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:44.540 align:middle line:90%
over and over again.

00:10:44.540 --> 00:10:47.530 align:middle line:84%
She's had it over and over
again, long before we existed.

00:10:47.530 --> 00:10:51.130 align:middle line:84%
One of the things that natured
used a climate catastrophe

00:10:51.130 --> 00:10:53.080 align:middle line:90%
to create was the human brain.

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:54.650 align:middle line:84%
We grew up on the
edge of glaciers.

00:10:54.650 --> 00:10:57.680 align:middle line:90%
We grew up in an age of ice.

00:10:57.680 --> 00:10:59.720 align:middle line:84%
We grew up overcoming
catastrophe.

00:10:59.720 --> 00:11:02.070 align:middle line:84%
That's how we got the
brains we have today.

00:11:02.070 --> 00:11:04.860 align:middle line:84%
Our task is to take
these two big challenges

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:08.190 align:middle line:84%
and to turn them into the
next great source of wonder.

00:11:08.190 --> 00:11:09.710 align:middle line:84%
Global warming
and carbon dioxide?

00:11:09.710 --> 00:11:11.580 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, that carbon
dioxide in the air

00:11:11.580 --> 00:11:14.960 align:middle line:84%
is just-- it's fuel and
energy waiting to be made.

00:11:14.960 --> 00:11:16.080 align:middle line:90%
So how do we do that?

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:19.080 align:middle line:84%
Well, I have a friend
who is the chief scientist

00:11:19.080 --> 00:11:20.550 align:middle line:90%
at NASA Langley.

00:11:20.550 --> 00:11:23.700 align:middle line:84%
And he wants to take
massive quantities of algae.

00:11:23.700 --> 00:11:26.170 align:middle line:84%
Algae are really good-- two
things are really good at this.

00:11:26.170 --> 00:11:29.060 align:middle line:84%
They really know how
to take carbon dioxide

00:11:29.060 --> 00:11:30.460 align:middle line:90%
and make the most of it.

00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:33.200 align:middle line:90%
Trees and algae.

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:35.080 align:middle line:84%
In fact, anything
that's green knows

00:11:35.080 --> 00:11:38.120 align:middle line:84%
how to take carbon dioxide
and make the most of it.

00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:40.270 align:middle line:90%
So encourage green things.

00:11:40.270 --> 00:11:41.840 align:middle line:84%
Now, the green
things are already

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:43.960 align:middle line:84%
encouraging themselves,
thanks to modern agriculture,

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:45.390 align:middle line:90%
which we're supposed to hate.

00:11:45.390 --> 00:11:47.120 align:middle line:84%
Our footprint on
the land, in order

00:11:47.120 --> 00:11:49.570 align:middle line:84%
to feed seven
billion people now,

00:11:49.570 --> 00:11:52.190 align:middle line:84%
is so much smaller than it used
to be that it's ridiculous.

00:11:52.190 --> 00:11:53.980 align:middle line:84%
Which means there are vast
amounts of former farmland

00:11:53.980 --> 00:11:54.679 align:middle line:90%
that have been--

00:11:54.679 --> 00:11:57.270 align:middle line:84%
Are you including aspects
like a nitrogen runoff

00:11:57.270 --> 00:11:58.260 align:middle line:90%
from industrial pollution?

00:11:58.260 --> 00:11:59.990 align:middle line:84%
No I'm not including
that for the moment.

00:11:59.990 --> 00:12:02.560 align:middle line:90%
But we could discuss that too.

00:12:02.560 --> 00:12:06.170 align:middle line:84%
The point is that forests are
taking over the empty farmland

00:12:06.170 --> 00:12:07.240 align:middle line:90%
that's been left behind.

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:10.940 align:middle line:84%
And forests are great at
processing carbon dioxide.

00:12:10.940 --> 00:12:12.820 align:middle line:84%
We can take algae and
turn them into fuel.

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:15.260 align:middle line:84%
Liquid fuel, we can turn
them into just about any kind

00:12:15.260 --> 00:12:16.500 align:middle line:90%
of energy source you want.

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:18.660 align:middle line:84%
And the trick is to raise
them in mass quantities

00:12:18.660 --> 00:12:21.070 align:middle line:84%
and get them to gobble that
stuff up out of the atmosphere

00:12:21.070 --> 00:12:24.250 align:middle line:84%
and turn it into hey, the
next great source of wealth.

00:12:24.250 --> 00:12:25.840 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of people
are concerned

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:27.877 align:middle line:84%
that humanity-- I mean, it's
such a complicated moment.

00:12:27.877 --> 00:12:29.310 align:middle line:84%
Because on the one
hand, we seem like we've

00:12:29.310 --> 00:12:31.179 align:middle line:84%
never been doing better.
-Right.

00:12:31.179 --> 00:12:33.030 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you and I have
discussed how people are living

00:12:33.030 --> 00:12:34.120 align:middle line:90%
longer and healthier lives.

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:34.820 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:12:34.820 --> 00:12:36.067 align:middle line:84%
Certainly, in
the industrialized

00:12:36.067 --> 00:12:36.800 align:middle line:90%
first-world countries.

00:12:36.800 --> 00:12:37.940 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:39.570 align:middle line:84%
And yet, a lot of
us feel that we're

00:12:39.570 --> 00:12:41.440 align:middle line:84%
teetering on the
brink of potentially

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:42.370 align:middle line:90%
annihilating ourselves.

00:12:42.370 --> 00:12:45.020 align:middle line:84%
If we look at the
oceans becoming

00:12:45.020 --> 00:12:50.910 align:middle line:84%
30% more acidic, the
species extinction crisis,

00:12:50.910 --> 00:12:52.940 align:middle line:90%
the coral reefs disintegrating.

00:12:52.940 --> 00:12:57.410 align:middle line:84%
Is your perspective, then,
that we're kind of, like,

00:12:57.410 --> 00:13:00.620 align:middle line:84%
in the process of kind of
overcoming these obstacles?

00:13:00.620 --> 00:13:02.900 align:middle line:84%
We are in the process of
overcoming the obstacles.

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:05.380 align:middle line:84%
All of the protest movements
against these problems

00:13:05.380 --> 00:13:08.040 align:middle line:84%
are extremely helpful in
overcoming the obstacles.

00:13:08.040 --> 00:13:09.850 align:middle line:84%
But we have to keep
from doing ourselves

00:13:09.850 --> 00:13:12.610 align:middle line:90%
in with a negative perception.

00:13:12.610 --> 00:13:16.210 align:middle line:84%
For example, since 18-- if we'd
been born at 1850-- the two

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:17.700 align:middle line:84%
of us sitting at this
table, the people

00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:19.630 align:middle line:84%
sitting in this room--
our life expectancy

00:13:19.630 --> 00:13:21.750 align:middle line:90%
would've been 38.5 years.

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:24.380 align:middle line:84%
If we'd been born in
2000, our life expectancy

00:13:24.380 --> 00:13:26.090 align:middle line:90%
would have been 78.5 years.

00:13:26.090 --> 00:13:28.850 align:middle line:84%
That's a doubling of
the human lifespan.

00:13:28.850 --> 00:13:34.690 align:middle line:84%
If we'd been the poorest-paid
worker in London in 1850

00:13:34.690 --> 00:13:36.330 align:middle line:84%
versus the poorest-paid
worker or being

00:13:36.330 --> 00:13:39.320 align:middle line:84%
the poorest-paid worker
in London in 2000.

00:13:39.320 --> 00:13:42.470 align:middle line:84%
In 2000 we would've earned
what an entire tenement

00:13:42.470 --> 00:13:47.300 align:middle line:84%
full of the poorest-paid workers
in London earned back in 1850.

00:13:47.300 --> 00:13:49.820 align:middle line:84%
Not to mention the fact that
there were things-- there was

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:52.680 align:middle line:84%
a techno freak back in
England, in 1850, who just-- he

00:13:52.680 --> 00:13:53.880 align:middle line:90%
loved the latest technologies.

00:13:53.880 --> 00:13:55.740 align:middle line:84%
He had all the
power in the world.

00:13:55.740 --> 00:13:58.220 align:middle line:84%
He was able to summon the
technologists from all

00:13:58.220 --> 00:14:01.130 align:middle line:84%
over the world to bring their
latest items to London just

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:02.040 align:middle line:90%
for his edification.

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:03.100 align:middle line:90%
He built a building for it.

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:04.280 align:middle line:84%
It was called the
Crystal Palace.

00:14:04.280 --> 00:14:06.290 align:middle line:90%
His name was Prince Albert.

00:14:06.290 --> 00:14:09.130 align:middle line:84%
And he died at something
like 42 years old.

00:14:09.130 --> 00:14:11.550 align:middle line:84%
He didn't have access
to the simple medicines

00:14:11.550 --> 00:14:12.970 align:middle line:84%
that the poorest
person in London

00:14:12.970 --> 00:14:16.420 align:middle line:84%
today would have
access to like that,

00:14:16.420 --> 00:14:18.260 align:middle line:90%
to solve their health problems.

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:21.330 align:middle line:84%
We have to recognize the
positives and build on them.

00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:23.470 align:middle line:84%
If we fail to recognize
the positives,

00:14:23.470 --> 00:14:26.100 align:middle line:84%
we humans have this
peculiar quality.

00:14:26.100 --> 00:14:28.610 align:middle line:90%
It is an apocalypse addiction.

00:14:28.610 --> 00:14:29.960 align:middle line:90%
And we come up with apocalypse--

00:14:29.960 --> 00:14:31.790 align:middle line:84%
Well, yeah, the word
apocalypse literally

00:14:31.790 --> 00:14:33.580 align:middle line:84%
means uncovering or revealing.
-Yes.

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:34.280 align:middle line:90%
But--

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:35.913 align:middle line:84%
So maybe you're talking
more of a catastrophic--

00:14:35.913 --> 00:14:37.760 align:middle line:84%
I'm talking catastrophic
apocalypse, as opposed

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:40.110 align:middle line:90%
to an apocalypse of revelation.

00:14:40.110 --> 00:14:42.720 align:middle line:84%
And so we believe
the world is ending.

00:14:42.720 --> 00:14:45.220 align:middle line:84%
But we've believed this
for tens of thousands

00:14:45.220 --> 00:14:46.770 align:middle line:90%
of years, over and over again.

00:14:46.770 --> 00:14:48.230 align:middle line:90%
It's never quite happened.

00:14:48.230 --> 00:14:52.390 align:middle line:84%
But it is possible to end an
entire civilization by focusing

00:14:52.390 --> 00:14:55.820 align:middle line:84%
only on disaster
and not seeing what

00:14:55.820 --> 00:14:57.100 align:middle line:90%
you're positively creating.

00:14:57.100 --> 00:14:59.190 align:middle line:84%
Because our job is
the positive creation.

00:14:59.190 --> 00:15:01.146 align:middle line:84%
-Look how excited you are.
-Yeah.

00:15:01.146 --> 00:15:02.190 align:middle line:90%
With this stuff.

00:15:02.190 --> 00:15:06.560 align:middle line:84%
But Daniel, look, I'm
70-freaking years old.

00:15:06.560 --> 00:15:11.390 align:middle line:84%
I did 330 push ups this
morning before I came here.

00:15:11.390 --> 00:15:15.690 align:middle line:84%
And it's because I'm doing
the stuff I care about.

00:15:15.690 --> 00:15:18.080 align:middle line:84%
And if we all do the
stuff we care about,

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:19.990 align:middle line:84%
just think how much
further we'll all-- I mean,

00:15:19.990 --> 00:15:20.960 align:middle line:90%
this planet will go.

