00:25:43.130 --> 00:25:45.420 align:middle line:90%
from 165 words.

00:25:45.420 --> 00:25:48.130 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course, if
that hypothesis is accurate,

00:25:48.130 --> 00:25:52.310 align:middle line:84%
if that's how the universe
does do her thing, why?

00:25:52.310 --> 00:25:54.490 align:middle line:84%
How in the world
does that happen?

00:25:54.490 --> 00:25:56.250 align:middle line:84%
How in the world can
these massive amounts

00:25:56.250 --> 00:26:02.790 align:middle line:84%
of implicit stuff be there in
just a handful of magic beans?

00:26:02.790 --> 00:26:04.500 align:middle line:84%
And what are you
foreseeing now?

00:26:04.500 --> 00:26:07.590 align:middle line:84%
Or how do you look at the near
future for human civilization,

00:26:07.590 --> 00:26:08.790 align:middle line:90%
and even for New York?

00:26:08.790 --> 00:26:12.440 align:middle line:84%
I mean, do you think New York is
in danger of being under flood

00:26:12.440 --> 00:26:15.520 align:middle line:90%
waters in 20 years, 30 years?

00:26:15.520 --> 00:26:18.620 align:middle line:84%
It's very hard for me to
judge the global warming

00:26:18.620 --> 00:26:19.940 align:middle line:90%
and climate change predictions.

00:26:19.940 --> 00:26:23.620 align:middle line:84%
Because I'm inside of science
in my own peculiar outsider way.

00:26:23.620 --> 00:26:26.800 align:middle line:84%
And what I've watched is
this incredible conformity

00:26:26.800 --> 00:26:29.140 align:middle line:84%
enforcement within the
scientific community,

00:26:29.140 --> 00:26:31.930 align:middle line:84%
to go along with the
concept of global warming,

00:26:31.930 --> 00:26:35.300 align:middle line:84%
and especially anthropogenic--
manmade-- global warming.

00:26:35.300 --> 00:26:37.180 align:middle line:90%
And the pressure's been intense.

00:26:37.180 --> 00:26:39.500 align:middle line:84%
It's been like the days
of the Inquisition.

00:26:39.500 --> 00:26:41.980 align:middle line:84%
If you didn't believe
in the program

00:26:41.980 --> 00:26:46.160 align:middle line:84%
and you didn't promote it you
were frozen out of science.

00:26:46.160 --> 00:26:48.550 align:middle line:84%
That's not how science is done.
Now--

00:26:48.550 --> 00:26:51.720 align:middle line:84%
So you have questions
whether anthropogenic climate

00:26:51.720 --> 00:26:53.200 align:middle line:84%
change is happening?
-Yes.

00:26:53.200 --> 00:26:56.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean, all the climate models
could be absolutely accurate.

00:26:56.700 --> 00:26:58.520 align:middle line:84%
New York could end up
under 30 feet of water.

00:26:58.520 --> 00:26:59.800 align:middle line:90%
That would be a disaster.

00:26:59.800 --> 00:27:01.630 align:middle line:84%
But one thing to
recognize, Daniel,

00:27:01.630 --> 00:27:04.340 align:middle line:84%
is that this has been
a planet of climate

00:27:04.340 --> 00:27:08.150 align:middle line:84%
change, massive climate change,
ever since the beginning.

00:27:08.150 --> 00:27:09.617 align:middle line:84%
Once upon a time, we
had snowball artists.

00:27:09.617 --> 00:27:10.850 align:middle line:84%
So whatever this
change is, it would

00:27:10.850 --> 00:27:13.282 align:middle line:84%
be a catalyst for
the next evolution

00:27:13.282 --> 00:27:14.315 align:middle line:90%
of human culture in some sense?

00:27:14.315 --> 00:27:16.920 align:middle line:84%
It's a catalyst for us
humans to wake up to the fact

00:27:16.920 --> 00:27:18.725 align:middle line:84%
that this is not a
planet of stasis.

00:27:18.725 --> 00:27:21.130 align:middle line:84%
That our ideas of
equilibrium-- as

00:27:21.130 --> 00:27:24.320 align:middle line:84%
in thermodynamic equilibrium
and ecological equilibrium--

00:27:24.320 --> 00:27:25.230 align:middle line:90%
are totally false.

00:27:25.230 --> 00:27:27.900 align:middle line:84%
They have nothing to do with
this universe we live in.

00:27:27.900 --> 00:27:32.590 align:middle line:84%
And that this is a universe in
a state of accelerating balance.

00:27:32.590 --> 00:27:33.510 align:middle line:90%
And it's a balance.

00:27:33.510 --> 00:27:35.520 align:middle line:84%
It's like you're
being on a bicycle.

00:27:35.520 --> 00:27:38.470 align:middle line:84%
You have to balance to the
left, balance to the right.

00:27:38.470 --> 00:27:39.970 align:middle line:84%
And if you don't
keep moving forward,

00:27:39.970 --> 00:27:41.460 align:middle line:90%
you're dead in the water.

00:27:41.460 --> 00:27:43.400 align:middle line:90%
So there is never a stasis.

00:27:43.400 --> 00:27:45.410 align:middle line:84%
There has never been
a Garden of Eden

00:27:45.410 --> 00:27:47.010 align:middle line:84%
on this planet that
has just stayed

00:27:47.010 --> 00:27:50.090 align:middle line:84%
wonderful, lush,
green and loving.

00:27:50.090 --> 00:27:51.110 align:middle line:90%
It's the other way around.

00:27:51.110 --> 00:27:54.050 align:middle line:84%
This been a vicious planet where
terrible things have happened.

00:27:54.050 --> 00:27:56.450 align:middle line:84%
We're the only ones who
conceive of just things.

00:27:56.450 --> 00:27:59.670 align:middle line:84%
Our job is to make justice
in this place of viciousness.

00:27:59.670 --> 00:28:00.940 align:middle line:90%
Mhm.

00:28:00.940 --> 00:28:03.490 align:middle line:84%
So how do you see,
potentially, human society

00:28:03.490 --> 00:28:05.490 align:middle line:84%
kind of evolving maybe, in
the next, like, half century?

00:28:05.490 --> 00:28:08.180 align:middle line:84%
I think we have-- and this
can't happen in half a century.

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:10.520 align:middle line:84%
But we have to know that
everything that's ever been

00:28:10.520 --> 00:28:12.370 align:middle line:84%
on a seashore
eventually has ended up

00:28:12.370 --> 00:28:15.530 align:middle line:84%
on the top of a
mountain, that this is

00:28:15.530 --> 00:28:18.190 align:middle line:90%
a planet of cataclysmic change.

00:28:18.190 --> 00:28:20.437 align:middle line:90%
That it is not safe to--

00:28:20.437 --> 00:28:22.370 align:middle line:84%
DANIEL PINCHBECK: Do we have
a-- does humanity have a role

00:28:22.370 --> 00:28:23.720 align:middle line:84%
in the planet in some sense?
As a supported organism?

00:28:23.720 --> 00:28:24.419 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:28:24.419 --> 00:28:26.300 align:middle line:84%
We've been changing
things dramatically.

00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:27.870 align:middle line:84%
But remember, we're
not the first things

00:28:27.870 --> 00:28:29.110 align:middle line:90%
to change things dramatically.

00:28:29.110 --> 00:28:31.020 align:middle line:84%
Look with those
cyanobacteria did

00:28:31.020 --> 00:28:34.030 align:middle line:84%
when they totally changed
the nature of the atmosphere

00:28:34.030 --> 00:28:35.150 align:middle line:90%
of the planet.

00:28:35.150 --> 00:28:40.455 align:middle line:84%
Look what flowers did when they
enlisted animals in order to be

00:28:40.455 --> 00:28:42.690 align:middle line:90%
their transport mechanisms.

00:28:42.690 --> 00:28:47.080 align:middle line:84%
Right now, we could say that
grain, wheat, barley, corn,

00:28:47.080 --> 00:28:51.430 align:middle line:84%
have basically suckered us into
finding, absolutely, the best

00:28:51.430 --> 00:28:54.310 align:middle line:84%
places for them to live, the
best genetic combinations

00:28:54.310 --> 00:28:55.750 align:middle line:90%
with which to survive.

00:28:55.750 --> 00:28:59.560 align:middle line:84%
I mean, boy, they're going
they-- hogs and cattle

00:28:59.560 --> 00:29:02.720 align:middle line:84%
and sheep-- are doing
incredible box office,

00:29:02.720 --> 00:29:04.150 align:middle line:90%
thanks to using us humans.

00:29:04.150 --> 00:29:04.850 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:04.850 --> 00:29:05.670 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:29:05.670 --> 00:29:07.250 align:middle line:90%
Suckering us into the process.

00:29:07.250 --> 00:29:09.160 align:middle line:90%
Well, but we do make change.

00:29:09.160 --> 00:29:11.570 align:middle line:84%
And we're the first
conscious change makers.

00:29:11.570 --> 00:29:13.600 align:middle line:84%
And we do have to know
that our cities will

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:14.950 align:middle line:90%
have to float at some point.

00:29:14.950 --> 00:29:18.820 align:middle line:84%
And it won't happen-- and we
have to be beyond just settling

00:29:18.820 --> 00:29:21.380 align:middle line:84%
a city on a shelf
next to a coast,

00:29:21.380 --> 00:29:23.160 align:middle line:84%
assuming the coast is
going to stay there.

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:23.859 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:29:23.859 --> 00:29:25.730 align:middle line:84%
The coast is never
going to stay there.

00:29:25.730 --> 00:29:30.030 align:middle line:84%
Our job is to make cities that
can float with the change.

00:29:30.030 --> 00:29:31.550 align:middle line:90%
Potentially out in space.

00:29:31.550 --> 00:29:33.760 align:middle line:84%
Yes, including
cities out in space.

00:29:33.760 --> 00:29:36.230 align:middle line:84%
Because you can take--
you can build a tin

00:29:36.230 --> 00:29:37.520 align:middle line:90%
can out of glass and steel.

00:29:37.520 --> 00:29:39.420 align:middle line:84%
You can make it from
the lunar regolith.

00:29:39.420 --> 00:29:42.820 align:middle line:84%
You can make it from the
rock and dust on the moon.

00:29:42.820 --> 00:29:44.730 align:middle line:84%
Or you can make it
from asteroid stuff.

00:29:44.730 --> 00:29:47.080 align:middle line:84%
You can rotate it to give
it artificial gravity.

00:29:47.080 --> 00:29:48.470 align:middle line:84%
You can make a
big enough to have

00:29:48.470 --> 00:29:51.040 align:middle line:90%
500 square miles of territory.

00:29:51.040 --> 00:29:55.280 align:middle line:84%
You can put forests, farms,
puppy dogs, wildlife,

00:29:55.280 --> 00:29:57.630 align:middle line:84%
lakes, everything that
you love, everything

00:29:57.630 --> 00:29:58.710 align:middle line:90%
that you want up there.

00:29:58.710 --> 00:30:00.320 align:middle line:84%
You can make real
estate in space.

00:30:00.320 --> 00:30:02.020 align:middle line:90%
And that's making ecosystems.

00:30:02.020 --> 00:30:04.410 align:middle line:84%
That's making new
homes for life.

00:30:04.410 --> 00:30:05.900 align:middle line:84%
Now, I mean, in
the '60s, there was

00:30:05.900 --> 00:30:07.350 align:middle line:84%
a lot of you know,
kind of looking

00:30:07.350 --> 00:30:08.464 align:middle line:90%
forward to space migration.

00:30:08.464 --> 00:30:09.850 align:middle line:84%
Like, Timothy Leary, obviously--
-Right.

00:30:09.850 --> 00:30:12.000 align:middle line:84%
 --was one of the people who
was involved in that idea.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.050 align:middle line:84%
And somehow, it's like
our culture drifted away

00:30:14.050 --> 00:30:17.780 align:middle line:84%
from that as kind of a
motivation or incentive

00:30:17.780 --> 00:30:19.120 align:middle line:90%
or even, like, an ideal.

00:30:19.120 --> 00:30:20.550 align:middle line:84%
Why do you think
there was that drift?

00:30:20.550 --> 00:30:22.050 align:middle line:84%
And do you think
it's possible that it

00:30:22.050 --> 00:30:23.690 align:middle line:84%
could be kind of
repositioned as-- as

00:30:23.690 --> 00:30:26.060 align:middle line:90%
a central focus for the future?

00:30:26.060 --> 00:30:28.650 align:middle line:84%
Societies go
through-- and humans,

00:30:28.650 --> 00:30:31.910 align:middle line:84%
you and I have done this--
we go through these flows.

00:30:31.910 --> 00:30:35.210 align:middle line:84%
And at some points we are
wildly exuberant about all kinds

00:30:35.210 --> 00:30:36.400 align:middle line:90%
of possibility.

00:30:36.400 --> 00:30:39.220 align:middle line:84%
And it's a biological thing
and a perceptual thing.

00:30:39.220 --> 00:30:41.240 align:middle line:84%
And then we go into
the opposite, where we

00:30:41.240 --> 00:30:42.370 align:middle line:90%
think everything is a danger.

00:30:42.370 --> 00:30:43.250 align:middle line:90%
Everything's a risk.

00:30:43.250 --> 00:30:45.010 align:middle line:84%
We want to recoil
from everything.

00:30:45.010 --> 00:30:49.110 align:middle line:84%
And since the 1960s, especially
since the early 1970s,

00:30:49.110 --> 00:30:52.350 align:middle line:84%
our society's been in that
recoil from the natural world,

00:30:52.350 --> 00:30:53.910 align:middle line:90%
as if everything is a danger.

00:30:53.910 --> 00:30:54.960 align:middle line:90%
Everything is a risk.

00:30:54.960 --> 00:30:56.640 align:middle line:90%
All we see are the dangers.

00:30:56.640 --> 00:30:57.960 align:middle line:90%
Hey, I got news for you.

00:30:57.960 --> 00:31:00.390 align:middle line:84%
The job of humanity is
to see the positive side

00:31:00.390 --> 00:31:02.590 align:middle line:90%
to why, to make it happen.

00:31:02.590 --> 00:31:06.110 align:middle line:84%
To make the next level
of evolution happen.

00:31:06.110 --> 00:31:08.280 align:middle line:84%
And if we don't do it,
the Chinese will do it.

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:10.970 align:middle line:84%
Because right now they
have the kind of exuberance

00:31:10.970 --> 00:31:15.770 align:middle line:84%
that we lost around 1973.
-The Chinese do?

00:31:15.770 --> 00:31:18.320 align:middle line:90%
Mhm.

00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:19.440 align:middle line:90%
So-- so what--

00:31:19.440 --> 00:31:21.780 align:middle line:84%
HOWARD BLOOM: You look
doubtful about that, Daniel.

00:31:21.780 --> 00:31:24.300 align:middle line:84%
Well, today-- I mean,
what do you think

00:31:24.300 --> 00:31:25.450 align:middle line:90%
is actually happening then?

00:31:25.450 --> 00:31:27.480 align:middle line:84%
You think that-- I mean,
there's-- I noticed--

00:31:27.480 --> 00:31:31.600 align:middle line:84%
in some of your work, a kind of
almost like a patriotic tinge

00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:34.284 align:middle line:84%
of kind of, like, the
US has some kind of role

00:31:34.284 --> 00:31:35.250 align:middle line:90%
to play or kind of potential.

00:31:35.250 --> 00:31:36.570 align:middle line:90%
I'm a wild American chauvinist.

00:31:36.570 --> 00:31:37.270 align:middle line:90%
Is that right?

00:31:37.270 --> 00:31:38.160 align:middle line:90%
I believe-- yeah.

00:31:38.160 --> 00:31:40.810 align:middle line:90%
I believe in freedom of speech.

00:31:40.810 --> 00:31:43.480 align:middle line:90%
I believe in pluralism.

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:45.300 align:middle line:90%
I believe in tolerance.

00:31:45.300 --> 00:31:48.240 align:middle line:84%
I believe in nourishing new
points of view, constantly.

00:31:48.240 --> 00:31:49.890 align:middle line:84%
But what about the
shadow aspects of America?

00:31:49.890 --> 00:31:53.090 align:middle line:84%
I mean, for instance, the
wars, the War on Drugs,

00:31:53.090 --> 00:31:55.070 align:middle line:84%
you know the massive
incarcerations of minority

00:31:55.070 --> 00:31:56.113 align:middle line:90%
populations and all that stuff?

00:31:56.113 --> 00:31:57.130 align:middle line:90%
Those things are hideous.

00:31:57.130 --> 00:32:00.260 align:middle line:84%
And under the president I voted
for, twice, Obama, they're

00:32:00.260 --> 00:32:02.260 align:middle line:90%
getting worse, of all things.

00:32:02.260 --> 00:32:03.880 align:middle line:84%
My president is
making things worse.

00:32:03.880 --> 00:32:06.960 align:middle line:84%
He doesn't seem to understand
the Constitution of the United

00:32:06.960 --> 00:32:08.800 align:middle line:90%
States and what it stands for.

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:09.670 align:middle line:90%
But guess what?

00:32:09.670 --> 00:32:12.570 align:middle line:84%
We still have the right to
protest against these things.

00:32:12.570 --> 00:32:16.840 align:middle line:84%
We still have the right to stand
up and be counted, stand up

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:19.640 align:middle line:84%
and stand in the way, to
become obstacles in the path,

00:32:19.640 --> 00:32:24.700 align:middle line:84%
and to make sure that the
principles that we believe in

00:32:24.700 --> 00:32:26.670 align:middle line:84%
are principles that
are instantiated,

00:32:26.670 --> 00:32:28.320 align:middle line:84%
that are turned
into realities, that

00:32:28.320 --> 00:32:30.830 align:middle line:84%
are reified in this country.
-Thank you.

00:32:30.830 --> 00:32:32.187 align:middle line:90%
What's your next book topic?

00:32:32.187 --> 00:32:33.420 align:middle line:84%
Do you have another
one in the works?

00:32:33.420 --> 00:32:36.320 align:middle line:84%
It's called "The Case of
the Consumerist Cosmos."

00:32:36.320 --> 00:32:38.540 align:middle line:84%
And it says that we are
making a massive mistake

00:32:38.540 --> 00:32:42.540 align:middle line:84%
in our definition of
nature, in our view

00:32:42.540 --> 00:32:44.360 align:middle line:90%
of what nature is all about.

00:32:44.360 --> 00:32:46.630 align:middle line:90%
That we loathe several things.

00:32:46.630 --> 00:32:49.790 align:middle line:84%
We loathe consumerism,
materialism,

00:32:49.790 --> 00:32:52.100 align:middle line:90%
vain display, and waste.

00:32:52.100 --> 00:32:54.540 align:middle line:84%
And we think those are
uniquely ours, uniquely

00:32:54.540 --> 00:32:56.670 align:middle line:90%
Western, uniquely capitalist.

00:32:56.670 --> 00:32:57.920 align:middle line:90%
And they're not.

00:32:57.920 --> 00:32:59.470 align:middle line:90%
They've been in the cosmos.

00:32:59.470 --> 00:33:01.140 align:middle line:84%
They've been a part
of the cosmic process

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:02.240 align:middle line:90%
since the very beginning.

00:33:02.240 --> 00:33:04.680 align:middle line:84%
I mean, nature,
just as an example.

00:33:04.680 --> 00:33:06.310 align:middle line:84%
Nature, once upon
a time, invented

00:33:06.310 --> 00:33:07.280 align:middle line:90%
this thing called death.

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:08.960 align:middle line:84%
She invented it in
the days after she

00:33:08.960 --> 00:33:12.290 align:middle line:84%
birthed the first stars and
she started to kill them off.

00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:17.650 align:middle line:84%
Death is the most materialist
throw-away wasteful thing

00:33:17.650 --> 00:33:19.300 align:middle line:90%
you can possibly imagine.

00:33:19.300 --> 00:33:20.320 align:middle line:90%
And it's vicious.

00:33:20.320 --> 00:33:21.770 align:middle line:90%
And it's cruel.

00:33:21.770 --> 00:33:23.560 align:middle line:90%
And it comes from nature.

00:33:23.560 --> 00:33:26.040 align:middle line:84%
So our job is to conceive
not only how to do

00:33:26.040 --> 00:33:28.190 align:middle line:90%
what nature does but better.

00:33:28.190 --> 00:33:30.000 align:middle line:84%
It's how to do what
nature does but with more

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.080 align:middle line:90%
warmth and compassion.

00:33:33.080 --> 00:33:35.850 align:middle line:84%
How does that relate
to the subject of death?

00:33:35.850 --> 00:33:39.215 align:middle line:90%
Well, death has got to go.

00:33:39.215 --> 00:33:41.075 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:41.075 --> 00:33:42.935 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:33:42.935 --> 00:33:45.270 align:middle line:90%


00:33:45.270 --> 00:33:46.390 align:middle line:90%
And we--

00:33:46.390 --> 00:33:48.100 align:middle line:90%
WOMAN: It's not going anywhere.

00:33:48.100 --> 00:33:49.990 align:middle line:90%
It's going somewhere.

00:33:49.990 --> 00:33:53.420 align:middle line:84%
We just heard a voice
from the gallery,

00:33:53.420 --> 00:33:55.480 align:middle line:84%
saying that death is
not going anywhere.

00:33:55.480 --> 00:33:56.560 align:middle line:90%
I got news for you.

00:33:56.560 --> 00:34:00.090 align:middle line:84%
Remember those figures
on 1850 and the lifespan

00:34:00.090 --> 00:34:02.280 align:middle line:90%
being 38.5 years?

00:34:02.280 --> 00:34:05.850 align:middle line:84%
And today it is 78.5
years and climbing.

00:34:05.850 --> 00:34:08.389 align:middle line:84%
Climbing at the rate of
three months for every year

00:34:08.389 --> 00:34:09.750 align:middle line:90%
that you're alive.

00:34:09.750 --> 00:34:13.510 align:middle line:84%
We, somehow, without knowing
it, are setting death

00:34:13.510 --> 00:34:17.050 align:middle line:90%
back big time, really big time.

00:34:17.050 --> 00:34:19.580 align:middle line:84%
And it's time for us
to wake up and stop

00:34:19.580 --> 00:34:21.690 align:middle line:84%
only glooming--
because that's what

00:34:21.690 --> 00:34:22.900 align:middle line:90%
we're focused on these days.

00:34:22.900 --> 00:34:25.580 align:middle line:84%
We're obsessed with
gloom-- and look

00:34:25.580 --> 00:34:27.679 align:middle line:84%
at what we are
accomplishing so we can

00:34:27.679 --> 00:34:29.590 align:middle line:90%
figure out how to do it better.

00:34:29.590 --> 00:34:32.179 align:middle line:84%
If our grandparents could
put you and me at the point

00:34:32.179 --> 00:34:35.199 align:middle line:84%
where our lifetimes are
twice as long as theirs,

00:34:35.199 --> 00:34:38.199 align:middle line:84%
it's our job to make sure
that our great grandkids have

00:34:38.199 --> 00:34:41.100 align:middle line:84%
lives that are four
times as long as ours.

00:34:41.100 --> 00:34:42.793 align:middle line:90%
And how do you see that?

00:34:42.793 --> 00:34:44.840 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that seems to
get back to these ideas

00:34:44.840 --> 00:34:47.739 align:middle line:84%
of the technological singularity
and the biotechnology

00:34:47.739 --> 00:34:49.080 align:middle line:84%
and nanotechnology
and their capacities.

00:34:49.080 --> 00:34:50.050 align:middle line:90%
We're not quite sure.

00:34:50.050 --> 00:34:52.429 align:middle line:84%
Because when we talk
about nanotechnology

00:34:52.429 --> 00:34:55.050 align:middle line:84%
and the singularity we're
talking as reductionists.

00:34:55.050 --> 00:34:58.180 align:middle line:84%
We're talking as if there's
just one silver bullet.

00:34:58.180 --> 00:34:59.060 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:34:59.060 --> 00:35:00.210 align:middle line:90%
This is not planet.

00:35:00.210 --> 00:35:02.570 align:middle line:84%
This is not a cosmos
of silver bullets.

00:35:02.570 --> 00:35:05.010 align:middle line:84%
This is a cosmos
of big pictures.

00:35:05.010 --> 00:35:08.160 align:middle line:84%
This is a cosmos of grand
tapestries and grand weaves.

00:35:08.160 --> 00:35:10.350 align:middle line:90%
It's a cosmos of recipes.

00:35:10.350 --> 00:35:12.310 align:middle line:84%
And we have to stop
looking at things

00:35:12.310 --> 00:35:15.100 align:middle line:84%
as one individual
thing is the answer.

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:16.410 align:middle line:90%
There are weaves of answers.

00:35:16.410 --> 00:35:19.770 align:middle line:84%
Why was I able to do
330 push ups today,

00:35:19.770 --> 00:35:22.640 align:middle line:84%
and it's a month after
I turned 70 years old?

00:35:22.640 --> 00:35:25.130 align:middle line:90%
Daniel, I don't know.

00:35:25.130 --> 00:35:28.840 align:middle line:84%
But whatever it is,
it's my job to find out

00:35:28.840 --> 00:35:31.610 align:middle line:84%
so that other people
can do it too.

00:35:31.610 --> 00:35:35.530 align:middle line:84%
And so what do you think
about capitalism itself?

00:35:35.530 --> 00:35:38.620 align:middle line:84%
I mean, some people
would say that you know,

00:35:38.620 --> 00:35:41.675 align:middle line:84%
it's-- obviously, it's
produced a lot of these amazing

00:35:41.675 --> 00:35:43.374 align:middle line:84%
effects that you've discussed.
-Right.

00:35:43.374 --> 00:35:44.580 align:middle line:84%
But that-- that
it's, obviously,

00:35:44.580 --> 00:35:46.040 align:middle line:84%
a very creative and
also, in some ways,

00:35:46.040 --> 00:35:47.580 align:middle line:90%
wasteful and destructive system.

00:35:47.580 --> 00:35:50.890 align:middle line:84%
Do you think that capitalism
or certain aspects of it

00:35:50.890 --> 00:35:52.030 align:middle line:90%
might be transitional?

00:35:52.030 --> 00:35:54.710 align:middle line:84%
Or do you feel that with
capitalism we discovered

00:35:54.710 --> 00:35:57.490 align:middle line:84%
something that's kind
of totally in alignment

00:35:57.490 --> 00:35:59.460 align:middle line:84%
with nature's principles
and that'll always

00:35:59.460 --> 00:36:00.790 align:middle line:90%
be with us in some sense?

00:36:00.790 --> 00:36:03.150 align:middle line:84%
Well, I think that
capitalism is totally aligned

00:36:03.150 --> 00:36:04.240 align:middle line:90%
with nature's principles.

00:36:04.240 --> 00:36:06.920 align:middle line:84%
Because just like nature,
we don't understand it.

00:36:06.920 --> 00:36:08.330 align:middle line:90%
We understood Marxism.

00:36:08.330 --> 00:36:11.190 align:middle line:84%
There was a nice big book
about it by Karl Marx.

00:36:11.190 --> 00:36:13.580 align:middle line:90%
It was a philosophy.

00:36:13.580 --> 00:36:14.700 align:middle line:90%
Capitalism is not a philosophy.

00:36:14.700 --> 00:36:16.010 align:middle line:90%
It grew of itself.

00:36:16.010 --> 00:36:18.200 align:middle line:84%
And we're not quite
entirely sure how.

00:36:18.200 --> 00:36:21.440 align:middle line:84%
Capitalism has its creative
aspect and it is phenomenal.

00:36:21.440 --> 00:36:23.620 align:middle line:84%
Look at Miki and
her wild pizzas.

00:36:23.620 --> 00:36:25.670 align:middle line:84%
Miki, who's about
to come up on stage,

00:36:25.670 --> 00:36:27.160 align:middle line:90%
at God knows what moment.

00:36:27.160 --> 00:36:29.910 align:middle line:84%
But at any great, her
pizzas are incredible.

00:36:29.910 --> 00:36:31.270 align:middle line:90%
She has an underwear company.

00:36:31.270 --> 00:36:33.280 align:middle line:84%
And the underwear company's
trying to accomplish things

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:35.970 align:middle line:90%
for girls that are phenomenal.

00:36:35.970 --> 00:36:38.280 align:middle line:84%
These are things that you
can do with capitalism.

00:36:38.280 --> 00:36:40.510 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm a
freaking science geek.

00:36:40.510 --> 00:36:42.470 align:middle line:84%
That's all I am, which
means I'm incapable of doing

00:36:42.470 --> 00:36:43.990 align:middle line:90%
anything real in life.

00:36:43.990 --> 00:36:47.871 align:middle line:10%
But I ran-- but I ran two
successful businesses.

00:36:47.871 --> 00:36:48.570 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:36:48.570 --> 00:36:50.940 align:middle line:84%
Because I needed to get out
there into the real world

00:36:50.940 --> 00:36:52.950 align:middle line:84%
and do some expeditions
and explore where

00:36:52.950 --> 00:36:54.170 align:middle line:90%
the wild ones were.

00:36:54.170 --> 00:36:56.030 align:middle line:84%
And capitalism
allowed me to do that.

00:36:56.030 --> 00:36:58.390 align:middle line:84%
And it was a phenomenal,
phenomenal experience.

00:36:58.390 --> 00:37:00.450 align:middle line:84%
Are there criminal
aspects to capitalism?

00:37:00.450 --> 00:37:01.730 align:middle line:90%
You bet.

00:37:01.730 --> 00:37:02.770 align:middle line:90%
But what's our job?

00:37:02.770 --> 00:37:05.760 align:middle line:84%
We don't tear cities apart
and go back to the countryside

00:37:05.760 --> 00:37:07.620 align:middle line:84%
because there are
muggers in the streets.

00:37:07.620 --> 00:37:09.050 align:middle line:90%
We stop the muggers.

00:37:09.050 --> 00:37:10.650 align:middle line:84%
And it's our job
to stop the muggers

00:37:10.650 --> 00:37:12.924 align:middle line:84%
in the capitalist system too.
-Awesome.

00:37:12.924 --> 00:37:14.390 align:middle line:84%
OK, well, listen, let's
take a little break.

00:37:14.390 --> 00:37:18.028 align:middle line:84%
And we'll come back with Miki
Agrawal and Amber Lasciak.

00:37:18.028 --> 00:37:19.161 align:middle line:84%
HOWARD BLOOM: All
right, terrific.

